      "**Raloxifene** is a benzothiophene-class selective estrogen receptor modulator (SERM) — mechanistically distinct from the triphenylethylene-class SERMs (Tamoxifen, Clomiphene). The structural class difference produces a substantially different tissue-selectivity profile, which is the central feature distinguishing Raloxifene from Tamoxifen and the principal driver of its preferred-status for several modern use cases. **Mechanism — tissue-selective receptor action**: like all SERMs, Raloxifene binds the estrogen receptor and produces tissue-specific agonist or antagonist effects depending on cell type and coactivator/corepressor recruitment. Raloxifene's profile: estrogen receptor antagonist in breast tissue (the cancer prevention indication), estrogen receptor agonist in bone (the FDA-approved postmenopausal osteoporosis indication), neutral or weak antagonist in uterus (no endometrial cancer signal — the central safety advantage over Tamoxifen), partial agonist in liver (modest favorable lipid effects), and substantially less penetration into the central nervous system than Tamoxifen (no cognitive fog signal — the second central advantage over Tamoxifen). **Mechanism — the Tamoxifen comparison**: this is where Raloxifene earns its preferred-status in informed protocols for non-cancer use cases. The principal differences:\n\n- **CNS penetration / cognitive fog** — Raloxifene crosses the blood-brain barrier substantially less than Tamoxifen; the cognitive fog signal documented in Tamoxifen cancer cohorts (Bender 2006/2007, Schilder 2010) is largely absent in Raloxifene literature; this is the central reason informed gyno-reversal protocols increasingly favor Raloxifene\n- **Endometrial safety** — Tamoxifen is a uterine agonist and increases endometrial cancer risk in long-term cancer use; Raloxifene is endometrially neutral\n- **Thromboembolic risk** — both have elevated thromboembolic risk; comparable between the two\n- **Hot flashes** — comparable to Tamoxifen, sometimes worse in some cohorts\n- **Fertility / HPTA stimulation context** — Tamoxifen has hypothalamic ER antagonism that drives FSH/LH rise (basis for legacy PCT use); Raloxifene's hypothalamic effects are weaker; Raloxifene is NOT a Tamoxifen substitute for HPTA recovery / fertility / PCT use cases\n\n**Mechanism — clinical reality across use cases**: (1) **Postmenopausal osteoporosis prevention and treatment** — FDA-approved indication; 60mg daily for fracture risk reduction in postmenopausal osteoporosis. (2) **Postmenopausal invasive breast cancer risk reduction** — FDA-approved indication based on STAR trial; 60mg daily; non-inferior to Tamoxifen for breast cancer prevention with substantially better safety profile. (3) **Gyno reversal in male users** — off-label but increasingly preferred over Tamoxifen in informed protocols; 60-120mg daily x 30-60 days; the breast-tissue ER antagonism produces tissue regression similar to Tamoxifen without the cognitive fog and with cleaner tolerability. (4) **NOT used for PCT / fertility / HPTA recovery** — Raloxifene's weak hypothalamic effects make it inappropriate for these contexts; Enclomiphene or Clomiphene are the workhorses. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability ~2% (substantial first-pass hepatic metabolism via glucuronidation); half-life ~28 hours; once-daily dosing standard; food does not significantly affect absorption. Steady state in 5 days. **Pharmaceutical status**: Raloxifene was developed by Eli Lilly, branded as Evista, FDA-approved 1997 for postmenopausal osteoporosis with subsequent approval expansion to breast cancer prevention (2007). Generic available since 2014; widely available pharmacy product. The off-label male gyno reversal use is clinically established but not FDA-labeled; coordination with prescriber is the standard path.",
