      "**Tadalafil** is a long-acting phosphodiesterase type 5 (PDE5) inhibitor — the longest-half-life PDE5 inhibitor in clinical use. **Mechanism — PDE5 inhibition and the cGMP cascade**: sexual stimulation in male users triggers nitric oxide release from neurons in the corpus cavernosum; NO activates guanylate cyclase, which converts GTP to cyclic GMP (cGMP); cGMP triggers smooth muscle relaxation in penile arteries, allowing increased blood flow and erection. PDE5 is the enzyme that breaks down cGMP, terminating the response. PDE5 inhibitors block this breakdown, sustaining cGMP and prolonging the smooth-muscle relaxation response. The mechanism requires sexual stimulation — PDE5 inhibitors do not produce erections without sexual arousal; they amplify and sustain the natural response. **Mechanism — the long-half-life advantage**: Tadalafil's ~17.5 hour plasma half-life produces the 'weekend pill' effect — a single dose maintains therapeutic plasma levels for 24-36 hours, allowing spontaneous sexual activity without close timing to dosing. This contrasts with Sildenafil (~3-5h), Vardenafil (~4-5h), and Avanafil (~5h) which require closer dose-to-activity timing. The long half-life also enables daily low-dose protocols (2.5-5mg daily) that maintain continuous PDE5 inhibition for endothelial function support, BPH symptom management, and broader cardiovascular themes. **Mechanism — BPH benefit (the second indication)**: Tadalafil is FDA-approved for benign prostatic hyperplasia (BPH) at 5mg daily based on smooth-muscle relaxation in prostatic and bladder neck tissue. Many users with combined ED and BPH benefit from daily 5mg dosing covering both indications. **Mechanism — pharmacokinetics**: oral bioavailability moderate; peak plasma 2 hours post-dose; half-life ~17.5 hours; not significantly affected by food (mild meal effect, much less than Sildenafil). **Pharmaceutical status**: Tadalafil was developed by Lilly ICOS (now Lilly), branded as Cialis (ED) and Adcirca (pulmonary arterial hypertension), FDA-approved 2003 for ED with subsequent approval expansion to BPH (2011) and PAH (Adcirca). Generic available since 2018; widely available pharmacy product. The TRT-context use as a companion drug for sexual function support is established in TRT clinic practice.",
