    notes:
      "## Clinical Context — The Original PDE5 Inhibitor and Situational Workhorse\n\nSildenafil is the most globally recognized PDE5 inhibitor — the original Viagra, FDA-approved 1998, and cultural shorthand for the entire PDE5 category. The accidental discovery from Pfizer's angina and hypertension research program in the early 1990s established the PDE5 inhibitor class and reshaped male sexual health pharmacology. In modern US clinical practice, Sildenafil retains substantial market share particularly for situational PRN use and as the lowest-cost PDE5 option for users with controlled timing.\n\nThe practical use case spans:\n\n**PRN ED management** — 50mg ~30-60 minutes before sexual activity on empty stomach; the standard situational pattern\n\n**Cost-driven PDE5 selection** — Sildenafil is typically the most aggressively cash-priced generic PDE5 inhibitor; for users with infrequent activity, the per-dose cost advantage vs Tadalafil can be substantial\n\n**Users with controlled timing** — Sildenafil's 4-6 hour therapeutic window suits planned sexual activity where dose-to-activity timing can be managed; less suited to spontaneous activity\n\n**Pulmonary arterial hypertension** — Revatio 20mg three times daily; clinical context coordinated with pulmonology / cardiology\n\n**TRT companion drug (situational)** — alternative to daily Tadalafil for TRT users who prefer PRN sexual function support over continuous daily dosing\n\n## Sildenafil vs Tadalafil — The Practical Decision\n\nSee the Tadalafil tile for the full PDE5 form-selection comparison. The core decision in modern PDE5 selection comes down to Sildenafil vs Tadalafil for most users (Vardenafil and Avanafil have narrower use cases):\n\n**Choose Sildenafil when:**\n- Cost is the primary driver (typically lowest per-dose cash price)\n- Sexual activity timing is controlled (planned encounters, predictable schedules)\n- Food intake can be managed (empty stomach dosing acceptable)\n- Daily medication is undesirable\n- Infrequent activity makes per-dose pricing preferable to monthly daily-dose cost\n\n**Choose Tadalafil when:**\n- Spontaneity is valued (24-36h therapeutic window)\n- BPH coverage is needed (combined ED + BPH at 5mg daily)\n- Food timing is unpredictable (mild meal effect vs Sildenafil's substantial food effect)\n- Daily dosing is preferred (5mg daily covers most situations)\n- Endothelial function support is a goal (continuous PDE5 inhibition)\n\nMost informed PDE5 selection in 2026 defaults to Tadalafil unless specific reasons argue for Sildenafil — but Sildenafil's cost advantage and PRN simplicity retain substantial appeal for many users.\n\n## The Food Effect — A Real Practical Issue\n\nSildenafil's absorption is substantially affected by food intake:\n\n- **Empty stomach (1+ hour after meal or before next meal):** absorption ~41% bioavailability, peak plasma 1 hour, predictable 30-60 minute onset\n- **High-fat meal (heavy dinner, fatty foods):** absorption delayed 60+ minutes, peak concentration reduced ~30%, less reliable onset\n- **Light meal:** moderate effect; less reliable than empty stomach but better than high-fat meal\n\nFor reliable onset, take Sildenafil on empty stomach. For users planning sexual activity around dinner, dose 30-60 minutes before dinner OR 1+ hour after dinner depending on meal composition. This food sensitivity is one of the principal drivers of Tadalafil preference for users with unpredictable meal timing.\n\n## TRT Companion Drug Context\n\nLike Tadalafil, Sildenafil pairs cleanly with TRT for users where testosterone optimization alone doesn't fully resolve erectile function. The choice between PRN Sildenafil and daily Tadalafil in TRT contexts depends on user lifestyle:\n\n- PRN Sildenafil for users with controlled timing and infrequent activity preferring lower medication exposure\n- Daily Tadalafil for users prioritizing spontaneity and continuous coverage\n\nMany TRT users start with PRN Sildenafil and transition to daily Tadalafil over time as the spontaneity advantage becomes apparent.\n\n## Counterfeit Sildenafil — A Global Concern\n\nSildenafil is the most widely counterfeited pharmaceutical globally. The combination of high demand, broad name recognition, and the embarrassment some users feel about prescription channels has driven substantial grey-market and counterfeit supply. Independent testing of grey-market 'Viagra' and generic sildenafil samples has documented:\n\n- Adulterated product with undisclosed active ingredients\n- Diluted product with sub-therapeutic Sildenafil content\n- Fake product with no Sildenafil at all\n- Contaminated product with impurities from substandard manufacturing\n\nLegitimate prescription channels (TRT-literate prescriber, modern direct-to-consumer telehealth, legitimate pharmacy) eliminate this risk for marginal cost increase. The grey-market cost savings are not worth the counterfeit risk for a medication where dose accuracy and purity affect both efficacy and safety.\n\n## Synergies\n\n**TRT testosterone esters** — TRT companion drug pattern; testosterone optimizes hormonal foundation, Sildenafil amplifies vasodilation. **PT-141** — central libido mechanism; different layer than PDE5; combination in select cases. **Oxytocin** — broader sexual function research themes; sometimes layered.\n\n## Clinical Trial Citations Worth Knowing\n\n**Viagra ED registration trials**: established efficacy at 25-100mg PRN; the foundational PDE5 inhibitor evidence base.\n\n**Revatio PAH trials**: established pulmonary arterial hypertension indication.\n\n**Long-term post-market surveillance**: 25+ years of widespread use; safety profile robust.\n\n## Evidence Quality\n\nMechanism well-characterized — the original PDE5 inhibitor and most thoroughly studied. ED indication evidence robust. Long-term safety profile well-characterized through generic-era widespread use.\n\n## Research vs Anecdote\n\nResearch: foundational PDE5 inhibitor evidence base; mechanism well-characterized; ED and PAH indications robust. Anecdote: substantial TRT and male sexual function community use base; consensus that Tadalafil > Sildenafil for users prioritizing spontaneity; consensus that Sildenafil > Tadalafil for cost-driven decisions and infrequent activity; consensus that food timing is real practical issue. Decision frame: original and most globally recognized PDE5 inhibitor; standard situational PRN choice; cost-advantaged vs Tadalafil for users with infrequent activity; food effect substantial — take on empty stomach for reliable onset; counterfeit risk substantial in grey-market channels; the catalog does not provide specific protocol guidance per locked HRT/protocol rule.",
